{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01JMU7c4ufjwvM1wanHb6Asi","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Improvement Plan — Iteration 4\n     2→\n     3→## Summary\n     4→\n     5→Four failures remain at 33.3% accuracy (2/6). All four share a common root cause: the dedup logic discards the correct multi-line join in favour of an incomplete substring. Two secondary issues compound the problem: the `firstStructuralHeading` check rejects joins containing continuation punctuation, and the position-inflated threshold excludes valid second titles on multi-recipe pages.\n     6→\n     7→Three targeted changes fix all four failures. No new embedding calls, no new dependencies. All changes are in `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`.\n     8→\n     9→---\n    10→\n    11→## Failure 1: ARAYES SHRAK → Got \"ARAYES\"\n    12→\n    13→**Root cause:** Dedup at line 335 removes the 2-line join `ARAYES SHRAK` because `rawScore(\"ARAYES\") >= rawScore(\"ARAYES SHRAK\")`. The shorter partial wins on a rawScore tie even though the join earned `firstStructuralHeading` bonus (+0.10) and `allCapsBonus` (+0.08) — neither of which is consulted during dedup.\n    14→\n    15→## Failure 2: Baked Eggs with Feta... → Got \"\"\n    16→\n    17→**Root cause:** Same dedup bug. The join `Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander` is removed because `rawScore(\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\") >= rawScore(full join)`. After dedup, the surviving candidates are the partial first line and orphaned `& Coriander`. Both may score too low to clear the `max(0.08, bestScore * 0.8)` threshold (since the join — which was the strongest candidate — was already eliminated). Result: `undefined`.\n    18→\n    19→## Failure 3: FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS → Got \"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\"\n    20→\n    21→**Root cause:** The position factor inflates the first title's score, which raises the threshold. `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS` (pos 0.37) gets `positionFactor ≈ 1.075`. `FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS` (pos 0.67) gets `positionFactor = 1.0`. The threshold is `0.8 × bestScore`, where bestScore includes the position boost. The second title's score (without position boost) falls below this inflated threshold and never reaches the multi-title guard at line 347.\n    22→\n    23→## Failure 4: SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D) → Got \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\"\n    24→\n    25→**Root cause:** Two compounding issues:\n    26→1. **Dedup:** Same as failures 1 & 2 — the join `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` is removed because the partial's rawScore >= the join's rawScore.\n    27→2. **`firstStructuralHeading` rejects the join:** The check requires every word to have ≥4 alpha letters. The token `\"/\"` has 0 alpha letters, so the join fails. Only the partial `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK` qualifies for the structural bonus. This creates asymmetric scoring that reinforces the dedup bug.\n    28→\n    29→---\n    30→\n    31→## Change 1: Use Final Score in Dedup, Prefer Longer on Ties\n    32→\n    33→### Problem\n    34→\n    35→Dedup compares `rawScore` (pure embedding similarity), ignoring all bonuses. But the bonuses encode structural signals (ALL_CAPS, first heading) that specifically indicate the join is the correct complete title. By ignoring these, dedup systematically discards the correct answer.\n    36→\n    37→Furthermore, the rule \"shorter wins on rawScore tie\" is backwards for the multi-line join case. When `ARAYES` and `ARAYES SHRAK` have equal rawScores, the longer string is the complete title — not a \"noisy join that happened to embed identically\" (the comment's justification). In practice, partial titles and their joins almost always have equal or near-equal rawScores because embedding models saturate on the core semantic content.\n    38→\n    39→### Code Change\n    40→\n    41→```typescript\n    42→// BEFORE (lines 327-338):\n    43→selected = selected.filter((a) => {\n    44→  const aLower = a.text.toLowerCase();\n    45→  return !selected.some((b) => {\n    46→    if (b === a) return false;\n    47→    const bLower = b.text.toLowerCase();\n    48→    // b is longer and contains a: remove a only when b is semantically stronger\n    49→    if (bLower.includes(aLower) && b.text.length > a.text.length && b.rawScore > a.rawScore) return true;\n    50→    // b is shorter and is contained in a: remove a when b is equally or more title-like\n    51→    if (aLower.includes(bLower) && b.text.length < a.text.length && b.rawScore >= a.rawScore) return true;\n    52→    return false;\n    53→  });\n    54→});\n    55→\n    56→// AFTER — use final score, prefer longer candidate on ties:\n    57→selected = selected.filter((a) => {\n    58→  const aLower = a.text.toLowerCase();\n    59→  return !selected.some((b) => {\n    60→    if (b === a) return false;\n    61→    const bLower = b.text.toLowerCase();\n    62→    // b is longer and contains a: remove a (shorter) when b has equal or higher score\n    63→    if (bLower.includes(aLower) && b.text.length > a.text.length && b.score >= a.score) return true;\n    64→    // b is shorter and contained in a: remove a (longer) only when b has strictly higher score\n    65→    if (aLower.includes(bLower) && b.text.length < a.text.length && b.score > a.score) return true;\n    66→    return false;\n    67→  });\n    68→});\n    69→```\n    70→\n    71→### Why this works\n    72→\n    73→The shift from `rawScore` to `score` means dedup now respects structural bonuses. The shift from \"shorter wins on tie\" to \"longer wins on tie\" reflects the reality that multi-line joins are completions, not noise.\n    74→\n    75→**ARAYES SHRAK:** `score(\"ARAYES SHRAK\")` includes `firstStructuralHeading` (+0.10) + `allCapsBonus` (+0.08) = rawScore × positionFactor + 0.18. `score(\"ARAYES\")` includes only `allCapsBonus` (+0.08) = rawScore × positionFactor + 0.08. Even if rawScores are equal, the join's score is +0.10 higher. Dedup now keeps the join and removes the partial.\n    76→\n    77→**Baked Eggs:** `score(\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\")` ≈ `score(\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\")` (neither is ALL_CAPS, no structural bonus). Since scores are approximately equal, the \"longer wins on tie\" rule keeps the full join and removes the partial. `& Coriander` is also removed as a substring of the join.\n    78→\n    79→**SAFFRON:** See Change 2 below — once the join qualifies for `firstStructuralHeading`, its score exceeds the partial's, and dedup keeps it.\n    80→\n    81→### Expected Impact\n    82→\n    83→| Case | Before | After |\n    84→|------|--------|-------|\n    85→| ARAYES SHRAK | \"ARAYES\" (join removed by dedup) | \"ARAYES SHRAK\" (join kept, partial removed) |\n    86→| Baked Eggs | \"\" (join removed, survivors too weak) | \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" (join kept) |\n    87→| SAFFRON (with Change 2) | \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" | Full title with continuation |\n    88→\n    89→---\n    90→\n    91→## Change 2: Continuation-Aware `firstStructuralHeading` and Candidate Joining\n    92→\n    93→### Problem\n    94→\n    95→Recipe titles split across lines often have continuation fragments starting with punctuation: `/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)`, `& Coriander`, `+ FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS`. The current `firstStructuralHeading` check requires every whitespace-delimited token to have ≥4 alpha letters. Tokens like `/`, `&`, `+`, `:`, and short parenthetical fragments like `D)` fail this check, so multi-line joins are excluded from the structural bonus even when they're the correct complete title.\n    96→\n    97→### Code Change — Strip continuation punctuation tokens before the structural check\n    98→\n    99→```typescript\n   100→// BEFORE (lines 272-280):\n   101→const firstStructuralHeading = candidates.find(\n   102→  (c) =>\n   103→    isAllCaps(c.text) &&\n   104→    wordCount(c.text) >= 2 &&\n   105→    c.text\n   106→      .trim()\n   107→      .split(/\\s+/)\n   108→      .every((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4)\n   109→);\n   110→\n   111→// AFTER — filter out continuation punctuation and short parenthetical tokens:\n   112→const CONTINUATION_TOKENS = /^[\\/&+:()]+$/;\n   113→const firstStructuralHeading = candidates.find((c) => {\n   114→  if (!isAllCaps(c.text) || wordCount(c.text) < 2) return false;\n   115→  const significantWords = c.text\n   116→    .trim()\n   117→    .split(/\\s+/)\n   118→    .filter((w) => !CONTINUATION_TOKENS.test(w));\n   119→  return (\n   120→    significantWords.length >= 2 &&\n   121→    significantWords.every((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4)\n   122→  );\n   123→});\n   124→```\n   125→\n   126→### Why this works\n   127→\n   128→For `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)`:\n   129→- Before: tokens include `/` (0 alpha) and `D)` (1 alpha) → fails\n   130→- After: `/` matches `CONTINUATION_TOKENS` → filtered out. Remaining significant words: `SAFFRON`(7), `WHEAT`(5), `BUNS`(4), `WITH`(4), `QUARK`(5), `COTTAGE`(7), `CHEESE`(6), `(VARIATION`→`VARIATION`(9), `D)`→`D`(1)...\n   131→\n   132→Hmm, `D)` has 1 alpha letter and doesn't match `CONTINUATION_TOKENS` since it's `D)` not pure punctuation. We need a slightly broader filter:\n   133→\n   134→```typescript\n   135→// Filter tokens that are: pure punctuation, single letter + punctuation, or parenthetical markers\n   136→const isInsignificantToken = (w: string): boolean => {\n   137→  const alpha = w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\");\n   138→  return alpha.length <= 1; // Covers \"/\", \"&\", \"+\", \":\", \"(\", \"D)\", \"1)\", etc.\n   139→};\n   140→\n   141→const firstStructuralHeading = candidates.find((c) => {\n   142→  if (!isAllCaps(c.text) || wordCount(c.text) < 2) return false;\n   143→  const significantWords = c.text\n   144→    .trim()\n   145→    .split(/\\s+/)\n   146→    .filter((w) => !isInsignificantToken(w));\n   147→  return (\n   148→    significantWords.length >= 2 &&\n   149→    significantWords.every((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4)\n   150→  );\n   151→});\n   152→```\n   153→\n   154→For `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)`:\n   155→- `/` → alpha \"\" (0) → insignificant, filtered\n   156→- `D)` → alpha \"D\" (1) → insignificant, filtered\n   157→- Significant words: SAFFRON(7), WHEAT(5), BUNS(4), WITH(4), QUARK(5), COTTAGE(7), CHEESE(6), `(VARIATION` → alpha \"VARIATION\"(9) → significant\n   158→- All significant words have ≥4 alpha letters → passes → gets structural bonus +0.10\n   159→\n   160→This gives the join a decisive score advantage over the partial, so Change 1's dedup keeps it.\n   161→\n   162→**Safety check — does this let \"DAT FLATBREADS\" through?**\n   163→- `DAT` → alpha \"DAT\" (3) → significant (>1 letter)\n   164→- Significant words: DAT(3), FLATBREADS(10). DAT has 3 < 4 → fails. Still blocked.\n   165→\n   166→### Expected Impact\n   167→\n   168→| Case | firstStructuralHeading before | After |\n   169→|------|-------------------------------|-------|\n   170→| SAFFRON join | fails (/ and D) have too few alpha) | passes (/ and D) filtered as insignificant) |\n   171→| ARAYES SHRAK | passes (no change) | passes (no change) |\n   172→| DAT FLATBREADS | fails (DAT has 3 letters) | still fails (DAT has 3 letters) |\n   173→\n   174→---\n   175→\n   176→## Change 3: Compute Threshold from Position-Free Scores\n   177→\n   178→### Problem\n   179→\n   180→The multi-title threshold `max(0.08, bestScore * 0.8)` uses the final score, which includes the position factor. The first title on a multi-recipe page gets a position boost that inflates `bestScore`, raising the bar. The second title — appearing later in the document — gets no position boost and may fall below this inflated threshold.\n   181→\n   182→This is a self-defeating interaction: the position factor is meant to be a tiebreaker between equally title-like candidates, but when it feeds into the threshold, it becomes a filter that excludes valid titles.\n   183→\n   184→### Code Change\n   185→\n   186→Store a position-free score alongside the final score and use it for threshold computation:\n   187→\n   188→```typescript\n   189→// In the scoring loop, compute both:\n   190→const scoreWithoutPosition = rawScore + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus;\n   191→const score = rawScore * positionFactor + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus;\n   192→scored.push({\n   193→  text: candidate.text,\n   194→  position: candidate.position,\n   195→  score,\n   196→  rawScore,\n   197→  baseScore: scoreWithoutPosition,  // NEW field\n   198→});\n   199→\n   200→// BEFORE (line 315):\n   201→const bestScore = Math.max(...scored.map((s) => s.score));\n   202→const threshold = Math.max(0.08, bestScore * 0.8);\n   203→\n   204→// AFTER — threshold based on position-free score:\n   205→const bestBaseScore = Math.max(...scored.map((s) => s.baseScore));\n   206→const threshold = Math.max(0.08, bestBaseScore * 0.8);\n   207→\n   208→// Still filter using final score (position factor is a valid ranking signal):\n   209→let selected = scored.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n   210→```\n   211→\n   212→### Why this works\n   213→\n   214→For the FINNISH case:\n   215→- `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS` (pos 0.37): `baseScore = rawScore + 0.08 + 0.10 = rawScore + 0.18`\n   216→- `FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS` (pos 0.67): `baseScore = rawScore + 0.08 = rawScore + 0.08`\n   217→\n   218→Before: `threshold = 0.8 × (rawScore × 1.075 + 0.18)`. The position factor (×1.075) inflates the threshold.\n   219→After: `threshold = 0.8 × (rawScore + 0.18)`. No position inflation.\n   220→\n   221→The second title's final score is `rawScore + 0.08`. For it to pass:\n   222→`rawScore + 0.08 >= 0.8 × (rawScore + 0.18)`\n   223→`rawScore + 0.08 >= 0.8 × rawScore + 0.144`\n   224→`0.2 × rawScore >= 0.064`\n   225→`rawScore >= 0.32`\n   226→\n   227→Recipe title headings typically score rawScore ≈ 0.10–0.20 against the title reference, so this threshold might still be tight. But removing the position inflation gives the second title a much better chance.\n   228→\n   229→**Additional safety valve:** If the second title still falls just below threshold, we can also lower the multiplier from 0.8 to 0.7:\n   230→\n   231→```typescript\n   232→const threshold = Math.max(0.08, bestBaseScore * 0.7);\n   233→```\n   234→\n   235→This is safer now that the threshold isn't position-inflated.\n   236→\n   237→### Expected Impact\n   238→\n   239→| Case | Before | After |\n   240→|------|--------|-------|\n   241→| FINNISH (2 titles) | Second title filtered by position-inflated threshold | Second title survives; multi-title guard (`allCapsSelected.length >= 2`) fires; both titles joined with \" + \" |\n   242→\n   243→---\n   244→\n   245→## Combined Impact Projection\n   246→\n   247→| Test Case | Current (iter 3) | After Changes | Which Changes |\n   248→|---|---|---|---|\n   249→| ARAYES SHRAK | FAIL (\"ARAYES\") | PASS (\"ARAYES SHRAK\") | Change 1: dedup keeps join (higher score from structural bonus) |\n   250→| Baked Eggs with Feta... | FAIL (\"\") | PASS (full title) | Change 1: dedup keeps join (longer wins on score tie) |\n   251→| FINNISH MILK + POTATO | FAIL (\"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\") | PASS (both titles) | Change 3: position-free threshold lets second title through |\n   252→| MIXED SEED CRISPBREAD | PASS | PASS | No regression — structural bonus + allCaps bonus still dominate |\n   253→| OVERNIGHT STRAIGHT PIZZA DOUGH | PASS | PASS | No regression — earliest candidate with highest semantic score + bonuses |\n   254→| SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS... | FAIL (partial) | PASS (full title with continuation) | Change 2: join qualifies for structural bonus; Change 1: dedup keeps it |\n   255→\n   256→**Projected accuracy: 6/6 (100%)**\n   257→\n   258→---\n   259→\n   260→## Risk Assessment\n   261→\n   262→### Regression risk for passing cases\n   263→\n   264→**MIXED SEED CRISPBREAD:** Currently passes because `firstStructuralHeading` selects it and gives it the decisive bonus. Change 2 modifies the structural heading check but only makes it more permissive (filters insignificant tokens). `MIXED SEED CRISPBREAD` has no insignificant tokens, so the check is unchanged. No regression.\n   265→\n   266→**OVERNIGHT STRAIGHT PIZZA DOUGH:** Currently passes because it's the earliest high-scoring ALL_CAPS candidate. Change 1 modifies dedup but this case has no substring relationships between candidates. Change 3 lowers the threshold slightly (position-free), which only allows more candidates through — it doesn't change which candidate scores highest. No regression.\n   267→\n   268→### Edge cases to watch\n   269→\n   270→1. **Cases where the shorter candidate genuinely IS the correct title and the join is noise.** The new rule \"longer wins on score tie\" could keep a noisy join over a clean short title. Mitigation: this only applies to substring relationships. If the join is noisy, it will fail `passesHardFilters` or score much lower on embedding similarity, so it won't be in a \"tie\" with the clean title.\n   271→\n   272→2. **Pages with many ALL_CAPS candidates.** The lower threshold (Change 3) may let more candidates through, increasing the chance of false multi-title detection. Mitigation: the multi-title guard (`allCapsSelected.length >= 2`) is structural, not threshold-based. The `cap at 3` and `sort by document position` logic handles overflow gracefully.\n   273→\n   274→3. **The `baseScore` field adds memory overhead.** One extra number per candidate, max 25 candidates = 200 bytes. Negligible on mobile.\n   275→\n   276→---\n   277→\n   278→## Implementation Checklist\n   279→\n   280→1. Add `baseScore` field to the scored candidates type\n   281→2. Modify `firstStructuralHeading` to filter insignificant tokens (≤1 alpha letter)\n   282→3. Compute `baseScore` (score without position factor) in the scoring loop\n   283→4. Change threshold to use `bestBaseScore` instead of `bestScore`\n   284→5. Change dedup to use `score` instead of `rawScore`, and invert tie-breaking (longer wins)\n   285→6. Run the test suite to verify all 6 cases pass\n   286→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_017VcW5mg8g8GLn5Xde6iMaH","session_id":"688165a7-dc9e-4c33-9dca-71554537d527","uuid":"2a11ee78-6a89-4040-992b-9a61d3b7474a"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01M5spoe9EjtbFLuYtn8fwGt","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Improvement Plan — Iteration 5\n     2→\n     3→## Root Cause Analysis\n     4→\n     5→### Failure 1: Baked Eggs (dedup kills continuation join)\n     6→\n     7→The 2-line join `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\"` is the correct title. The dedup \"shorter wins\" filter removes it because the single-line candidate `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\"` is a substring and shorter. The pre-filter at lines 344–352 only protects joins that match `firstStructuralHeading` — this mixed-case join gets no protection.\n     8→\n     9→**Core problem:** The pipeline has no concept of \"this candidate was built by joining lines whose second part starts with a continuation character\" — so it can't distinguish a legitimate continuation join from title+noise.\n    10→\n    11→### Failure 2: Finnish Flatbreads (second structural heading suppressed)\n    12→\n    13→Both `FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS` and `FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS` pass `isStructuralHeading`, but only the first receives `structuralBonus` (+0.10). The second title's `baseScore` falls below the threshold (`bestBaseScore * 0.7`) inflated by the first title's bonus.\n    14→\n    15→**Core problem:** `structuralBonus` is exclusive to `firstStructuralHeading`. On multi-recipe pages, subsequent structural headings are penalised by the very threshold their sibling inflated.\n    16→\n    17→### Failure 3: Saffron Wheat Buns (OCR garbage + dedup compound)\n    18→\n    19→Two compounding bugs:\n    20→1. `candidates.find(isStructuralHeading)` picks the first match — `\"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)\"`, an OCR-corrupted fragment from the previous recipe. It gets `structuralBonus` +0.10.\n    21→2. The correct 2-line join `\"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\"` is deduped away by its own first-line fragment (same mechanism as Failure 1).\n    22→\n    23→**Core problem:** `baseHeading` selection is purely positional (first match wins) with no quality signal. The OCR fragment looks structurally valid to `isStructuralHeading`.\n    24→\n    25→---\n    26→\n    27→## Proposed Changes\n    28→\n    29→### Change 1: Track join origin in `buildCandidates`\n    30→\n    31→**What:** Add a `joinType` field to candidate objects: `\"single\"`, `\"2-line\"`, or `\"3-line\"`. This metadata enables downstream logic to distinguish joins from single-line candidates.\n    32→\n    33→**Where:** `buildCandidates` function, lines 163–231.\n    34→\n    35→**Before:**\n    36→```ts\n    37→function buildCandidates(\n    38→  lines: Array<string>\n    39→): Array<{ text: string; position: number }> {\n    40→```\n    41→\n    42→**After:**\n    43→```ts\n    44→type CandidateOrigin = \"single\" | \"2-line\" | \"3-line\";\n    45→\n    46→function buildCandidates(\n    47→  lines: Array<string>\n    48→): Array<{ text: string; position: number; origin: CandidateOrigin }> {\n    49→```\n    50→\n    51→Each `candidates.push(...)` call tags the origin accordingly. Single-line pushes get `origin: \"single\"`, 2-line joins get `origin: \"2-line\"`, 3-line joins get `origin: \"3-line\"`.\n    52→\n    53→**Impact:** No behavioral change by itself. Enables Changes 2 and 4.\n    54→\n    55→---\n    56→\n    57→### Change 2: Protect continuation joins from dedup (fixes Failures 1 and 3)\n    58→\n    59→**What:** Before the dedup filter, remove single-line candidates that are prefixes of a multi-line join whose continuation part starts with a known continuation character (`/`, `&`, `+`, `:`, `(`). This generalizes the existing structural-heading pre-filter (lines 344–352) to ALL continuation joins, not just structural headings.\n    60→\n    61→**Where:** New block inserted between the structural-heading pre-filter (line 352) and the dedup filter (line 359).\n    62→\n    63→**Logic:**\n    64→```ts\n    65→// Protect continuation joins: when a multi-line join exists and its second part\n    66→// begins with a continuation character, remove the single-line prefix candidate\n    67→// so dedup doesn't kill the complete join.\n    68→const continuationJoins = selected.filter((s) => {\n    69→  const c = candidates.find((orig) => orig.text === s.text);\n    70→  return c && (c.origin === \"2-line\" || c.origin === \"3-line\");\n    71→});\n    72→if (continuationJoins.length > 0) {\n    73→  selected = selected.filter((s) => {\n    74→    // Keep if it's not a single-line candidate\n    75→    const c = candidates.find((orig) => orig.text === s.text);\n    76→    if (!c || c.origin !== \"single\") return true;\n    77→    // Remove if a continuation join starts with this text + continuation char\n    78→    const sLower = s.text.toLowerCase();\n    79→    return !continuationJoins.some((j) => {\n    80→      const jLower = j.text.toLowerCase();\n    81→      if (!jLower.startsWith(sLower + \" \")) return false;\n    82→      const remainder = jLower.slice(sLower.length + 1);\n    83→      return /^[/&+:(]/.test(remainder);\n    84→    });\n    85→  });\n    86→}\n    87→```\n    88→\n    89→**Why this is safe:** The Pierogi Ruskie case is unaffected — `\"Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki 3 ziemniaki\"` is a join whose continuation does NOT start with a continuation character (it starts with `\"200g\"`), so the prefix `\"Pierogi Ruskie\"` is preserved and dedup still picks the shorter form. The dedup block itself remains completely untouched (respecting the guard comment).\n    90→\n    91→**Expected impact:** Fixes Failure 1 (Baked Eggs) and the secondary bug in Failure 3 (Saffron dedup).\n    92→\n    93→---\n    94→\n    95→### Change 3: Give `structuralBonus` to ALL structural headings (fixes Failure 2)\n    96→\n    97→**What:** Replace the exclusive first-heading bonus with a bonus for every candidate that passes `isStructuralHeading`. Reduce the bonus from +0.10 to +0.06 to compensate for broader application, and keep a smaller +0.04 \"first heading\" bonus.\n    98→\n    99→**Where:** Scoring loop, line 315–316.\n   100→\n   101→**Before:**\n   102→```ts\n   103→const structuralBonus =\n   104→  firstStructuralHeading && candidate === firstStructuralHeading ? 0.10 : 0;\n   105→```\n   106→\n   107→**After:**\n   108→```ts\n   109→// Give a base structural bonus to ALL structural headings, with a smaller\n   110→// first-heading tiebreaker so the earliest heading wins among equals.\n   111→const isStructural = isStructuralHeading(candidate);\n   112→const structuralBonus = isStructural ? 0.06 : 0;\n   113→const firstHeadingBonus =\n   114→  firstStructuralHeading && candidate === firstStructuralHeading ? 0.04 : 0;\n   115→```\n   116→\n   117→Update `baseScore` and `score` to include `firstHeadingBonus`:\n   118→```ts\n   119→const baseScore = rawScore + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus + firstHeadingBonus;\n   120→const score = rawScore * positionFactor + allCapsBonus + structuralBonus + firstHeadingBonus;\n   121→```\n   122→\n   123→**Why this works:** On the Finnish Flatbreads page, both titles now get +0.06 structural bonus. The first title still gets a +0.04 edge, but the second title's baseScore is only 0.04 below (instead of 0.10), which keeps it above the `bestBaseScore * 0.7` threshold. The first-heading tiebreaker preserves existing behavior for single-recipe pages.\n   124→\n   125→**Expected impact:** Fixes Failure 2 (Finnish Flatbreads). Also reduces the damage from a garbage fragment claiming `firstStructuralHeading` (Failure 3) since the bonus gap shrinks from 0.10 to 0.04.\n   126→\n   127→---\n   128→\n   129→### Change 4: Select `baseHeading` by embedding quality, not position (fixes Failure 3)\n   130→\n   131→**What:** Instead of `candidates.find(isStructuralHeading)` (first positional match), defer `baseHeading` selection until after embeddings are computed. Pick the structural heading with the highest `rawScore` (embedding-only, no bonuses).\n   132→\n   133→**Where:** Move structural heading selection from lines 278–292 to after the embedding scoring loop (after line 323).\n   134→\n   135→**Before (line 278):**\n   136→```ts\n   137→const baseHeading = candidates.find(isStructuralHeading);\n   138→```\n   139→\n   140→**After (after scoring loop):**\n   141→```ts\n   142→// Select baseHeading from structural headings using embedding quality,\n   143→// not just position. This prevents OCR garbage from claiming the slot.\n   144→const structuralCandidates = scored.filter((s) =>\n   145→  isStructuralHeading(candidates.find((c) => c.text === s.text)!)\n   146→);\n   147→const baseHeadingScored = structuralCandidates.length > 0\n   148→  ? structuralCandidates.reduce((a, b) => a.rawScore > b.rawScore ? a : b)\n   149→  : null;\n   150→const baseHeading = baseHeadingScored\n   151→  ? candidates.find((c) => c.text === baseHeadingScored.text)!\n   152→  : undefined;\n   153→```\n   154→\n   155→The continuation logic (lines 285–292) and `firstStructuralHeading` derivation remain the same but now operate on the embedding-validated base heading.\n   156→\n   157→**Why this works:** `\"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)\"` is OCR garbage — its embedding similarity to the title reference is low. `\"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\"` is a real recipe title and scores higher with MiniLM. The correct heading wins the `baseHeading` slot, continuation logic fires correctly to produce the full join, and the pre-filter protects it from dedup.\n   158→\n   159→**Performance note:** No additional embedding calls — we simply reorder when the selection happens within the existing loop.\n   160→\n   161→**Expected impact:** Fixes the primary bug in Failure 3 (wrong baseHeading).\n   162→\n   163→---\n   164→\n   165→### Change 5: Add OCR-fragment heuristic to `isStructuralHeading`\n   166→\n   167→**What:** Add a lightweight heuristic: if the first significant word of an ALL_CAPS candidate does not appear in a dictionary of common English food/cooking words AND has fewer than 4 characters, demote it. More practically: check if any significant word looks like a truncated fragment by testing whether it starts mid-word (no English word starts with consonant clusters like \"FR\" + vowel pattern that doesn't form a word).\n   168→\n   169→Actually, a simpler and more robust approach: check if any significant word in the candidate is a substring of a significant word in another structural heading candidate. If `\"FRON\"` is a suffix-truncation of `\"SAFFRON\"` (from another candidate), penalize it.\n   170→\n   171→**Where:** After building `structuralCandidates` (from Change 4), add a cross-candidate validation step.\n   172→\n   173→**Logic:**\n   174→```ts\n   175→// Penalize structural headings where a significant word looks like a truncation\n   176→// of a word in another structural heading (OCR corruption detection).\n   177→for (const sc of structuralCandidates) {\n   178→  const sigWords = sc.text.split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4);\n   179→  for (const other of structuralCandidates) {\n   180→    if (other === sc) continue;\n   181→    const otherSigWords = other.text.split(/\\s+/).filter((w) => w.replace(/[^A-Z]/g, \"\").length >= 4);\n   182→    for (const word of sigWords) {\n   183→      if (otherSigWords.some((ow) => ow !== word && ow.endsWith(word))) {\n   184→        // word looks like a truncated version of a word in another heading\n   185→        sc.rawScore -= 0.15;\n   186→        break;\n   187→      }\n   188→    }\n   189→  }\n   190→}\n   191→```\n   192→\n   193→This catches `FRON` being a suffix of `SAFFRON` — the candidate `\"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)\"` gets a -0.15 penalty, ensuring it loses to `\"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\"` in `baseHeading` selection.\n   194→\n   195→**Expected impact:** Additional safety net for Failure 3 pattern. Won't fire on false positives because it requires another structural heading to contain the full word.\n   196→\n   197→---\n   198→\n   199→## Summary of Changes and Expected Impact\n   200→\n   201→| Change | Fixes | Risk | Lines touched |\n   202→|---|---|---|---|\n   203→| 1. Track join origin | Enables 2 & 4 | None (metadata only) | `buildCandidates` |\n   204→| 2. Protect continuation joins | Failures 1, 3 (secondary) | Low — continuation char guard prevents false matches | New block before dedup |\n   205→| 3. Distribute structuralBonus | Failure 2 | Low — smaller per-candidate bonus, first-heading tiebreaker preserved | Scoring loop (2 lines) |\n   206→| 4. Embedding-based baseHeading | Failure 3 (primary) | Low — better signal, same candidates | Move selection after embedding loop |\n   207→| 5. OCR truncation penalty | Failure 3 (defense in depth) | Very low — only fires when cross-candidate word match exists | New post-scoring block |\n   208→\n   209→### Performance\n   210→\n   211→- **No additional embedding calls.** Changes 1–5 add only lightweight string operations and reorder existing logic.\n   212→- **No new dependencies.** All changes are within `title-extractor.ts`.\n   213→- **Mobile-safe.** The added loops iterate over at most 25 candidates (existing cap) with simple string comparisons.\n   214→\n   215→### Expected Accuracy Impact\n   216→\n   217→- **Failure 1 (Baked Eggs):** Fixed by Change 2. The continuation join is protected; dedup no longer kills it.\n   218→- **Failure 2 (Finnish Flatbreads):** Fixed by Change 3. Both structural headings get bonus; second title passes threshold.\n   219→- **Failure 3 (Saffron Wheat Buns):** Fixed by Changes 4+5 (correct baseHeading selection) and Change 2 (correct join preserved through dedup).\n   220→\n   221→### Regression Risks\n   222→\n   223→- **Pierogi Ruskie dedup:** Unaffected. The join `\"Pierogi Ruskie 200g mąki...\"` does not start with a continuation character after the prefix, so Change 2 doesn't protect it. Dedup correctly picks the shorter form.\n   224→- **ARAYES SHRAK structural prefix removal:** Unaffected. The existing pre-filter at lines 344–352 still fires for structural heading prefixes. Change 2 adds a parallel path for non-structural continuation joins.\n   225→- **Single-recipe pages:** Change 3 gives +0.06 structural bonus to the sole structural heading (vs +0.10 before) plus +0.04 first-heading bonus = +0.10 total. Net effect is identical.\n   226→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_017VcW5mg8g8GLn5Xde6iMaH","session_id":"688165a7-dc9e-4c33-9dca-71554537d527","uuid":"44dcb0ab-4c28-4627-bdb7-1652a4870d7d"}
