{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01VcSRSWWgGS2NeJztncGxgJ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_016e1dsXJkP1MZe8BwteX5df","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/Users/eryk.napierala/Projects/fasola/tools/title-loop/docs/8-b5177f1/improvement-plan.md"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":7,"cache_creation_input_tokens":20469,"cache_read_input_tokens":59389,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":20469,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_017VcW5mg8g8GLn5Xde6iMaH","session_id":"688165a7-dc9e-4c33-9dca-71554537d527","uuid":"0be1e764-8877-4eb2-9ebb-caf4f31c428a"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Dzycd1V3Jbp4UBSnBkzmqN","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Improvement Plan — Iteration 8\n     2→\n     3→## Executive Summary\n     4→\n     5→Three of the four failures share a common root cause: the algorithm treats structural signals (ALL_CAPS, continuation characters, document position) as secondary bonuses on top of embedding scores, when in fact these structural signals are often **more reliable** than embeddings for determining recipe titles. The fix is to promote structural signals from \"bonus modifiers\" to \"pipeline-shaping decisions\" that happen before embedding scoring.\n     6→\n     7→The fourth failure (SAFFRON/OCR mismatch) is an evaluation harness issue, not an algorithm issue.\n     8→\n     9→---\n    10→\n    11→## Change 1: Pre-merge continuation lines before candidate generation\n    12→\n    13→**Fixes:** Failure 1 (Baked Eggs), Failure 4B (SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS join excluded from top-25)\n    14→\n    15→### Root Cause\n    16→\n    17→Continuation joins are fragile because they depend on a long chain of conditions all being true simultaneously:\n    18→1. The 2-line join must pass `passesHardFilters` (80 char limit can exclude long joins)\n    19→2. The join must survive the top-25 pre-filter (longer word count deprioritized)\n    20→3. The join must score above the embedding threshold independently\n    21→4. The `survivingJoins` protection must fire (requires join in `selected`)\n    22→5. Dedup \"shorter wins\" must not kill the join\n    23→\n    24→If ANY of these fail, the algorithm silently returns the truncated first half. This has been the single most persistent failure pattern across all 7 iterations — every attempt to patch it downstream has introduced new edge cases.\n    25→\n    26→### Proposed Fix\n    27→\n    28→Move continuation merging **upstream**, into `buildCandidates`, before candidates are generated:\n    29→\n    30→```typescript\n    31→// NEW: Pre-merge continuation lines before candidate generation.\n    32→// A continuation line starts with /&+:( — it's never a standalone title.\n    33→const mergedLines: Array<{ text: string; index: number }> = [];\n    34→for (let i = 0; i < nonEmptyLines.length; i++) {\n    35→  const line = nonEmptyLines[i];\n    36→  // Check if the NEXT line starts with a continuation character\n    37→  if (i + 1 < nonEmptyLines.length) {\n    38→    const nextText = nonEmptyLines[i + 1].text;\n    39→    if (/^[/&+:(]/.test(nextText)) {\n    40→      // Merge next line into this one\n    41→      mergedLines.push({\n    42→        text: `${line.text} ${nextText}`,\n    43→        index: line.index,\n    44→      });\n    45→      i++; // Skip the continuation line\n    46→      continue;\n    47→    }\n    48→  }\n    49→  mergedLines.push(line);\n    50→}\n    51→```\n    52→\n    53→Then use `mergedLines` instead of `nonEmptyLines` for candidate generation.\n    54→\n    55→### Before / After\n    56→\n    57→**Before (Baked Eggs):**\n    58→- Candidate pool contains: `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce\"` (single), `\"& Coriander\"` (single), and `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\"` (2-line join)\n    59→- The join must independently survive threshold, pre-filter, and dedup\n    60→- `\"& Coriander\"` pollutes the candidate pool as a standalone candidate\n    61→- If the join's embedding score is lower than the single's, protection logic doesn't fire → returns truncated title\n    62→\n    63→**After (Baked Eggs):**\n    64→- Lines 1+2 pre-merged into `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\"`\n    65→- Candidate pool contains this as a **single** candidate with `origin: \"single\"`\n    66→- `\"& Coriander\"` never enters the pool as standalone\n    67→- No dependence on join survival, threshold, or dedup — the merged line IS the candidate\n    68→- Result: `\"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\"` ✓\n    69→\n    70→**Before (SAFFRON):**\n    71→- `\"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\"` (5 words, ALL_CAPS) and `\"/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\"` (single) enter pool separately\n    72→- The 2-line join `\"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\"` (9 words) is deprioritized in the top-25 pre-filter (word count > 5)\n    73→- With ~45 non-empty lines after garbled burst, the join may be cut\n    74→\n    75→**After (SAFFRON):**\n    76→- Lines 54+55 pre-merged into `\"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\"`\n    77→- Enters pool as a single candidate, not subject to join-specific deprioritization\n    78→- `\"/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\"` never enters pool as standalone\n    79→- Result: `\"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\"` ✓\n    80→\n    81→### Impact on Existing Tests\n    82→\n    83→This change is **safe for existing passing tests**:\n    84→- ARAYES SHRAK: line 2 is `\"SHRAK\"` which does NOT start with `/&+:(` → no pre-merge, existing logic handles it\n    85→- FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS: second title starts with `\"FINNISH\"`, not a continuation char → no pre-merge\n    86→- Pierogi Ruskie: no continuation lines → unchanged\n    87→- All other passing tests: no continuation lines\n    88→\n    89→### Cleanup\n    90→\n    91→With pre-merging in place, the downstream `survivingJoins` continuation protection block (lines ~390-418 in current code) becomes largely redundant for continuation-character joins. It can be simplified but should be kept for non-continuation 2-line joins (e.g., titles that happen to span two lines without a leading symbol).\n    92→\n    93→---\n    94→\n    95→## Change 2: Ingredient-gap detection in multi-title guard\n    96→\n    97→**Fixes:** Failure 2 (CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM)\n    98→\n    99→### Root Cause\n   100→\n   101→The multi-title guard at lines 441-448 uses a simple rule: if `allCapsSelected.length >= 2`, return all ALL_CAPS candidates joined with `+`. This cannot distinguish between:\n   102→- **Multi-recipe pages** (two independent recipe titles): FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS + FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\n   103→- **Single-recipe pages with section headers**: CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM (title) + WARZYWA I BOCZEK (ingredient section header)\n   104→\n   105→The input for CHLEBEK shows:\n   106→```\n   107→Line 2: CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM  ← title\n   108→Line 3: WARZYWA I BOCZEK                ← section header\n   109→Line 4: 500 g strączków zielonego groszku  ← ingredient (has measurement!)\n   110→Line 5: 1 żółta papryka                    ← ingredient (starts with number!)\n   111→...\n   112→Line 9: CHLEBEK                          ← another section header\n   113→Line 10: 500 g mąki                      ← ingredient\n   114→```\n   115→\n   116→Between and after the ALL_CAPS headings, there are ingredient lines with measurements and numbers. On a multi-recipe page (like FINNISH FLATBREADS), the second recipe title appears after the FIRST recipe's body text ends, typically after a page break or significant gap — NOT immediately followed by ingredients that clearly belong to the preceding heading.\n   117→\n   118→### Proposed Fix\n   119→\n   120→Add an ingredient-gap check to the multi-title guard. When `allCapsSelected.length >= 2`, examine the original lines between each pair of ALL_CAPS headings. If ingredient-like content (lines with measurements or starting with numbers) appears between them, they are section headers within the same recipe.\n   121→\n   122→```typescript\n   123→// Inside the multi-title guard, after finding allCapsSelected.length >= 2:\n   124→if (allCapsSelected.length >= 2) {\n   125→  // Check if ALL_CAPS headings are separated by ingredient-like content\n   126→  // (measurements, numbered items) — if so, they're section headers\n   127→  // within a single recipe, not separate recipe titles.\n   128→  const sortedCaps = [...allCapsSelected].sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position);\n   129→  const firstPos = sortedCaps[0].position;\n   130→  const lastPos = sortedCaps[sortedCaps.length - 1].position;\n   131→\n   132→  const linesBetween = lines.slice(firstPos + 1, lastPos);\n   133→  const hasIngredientsBetween = linesBetween.some(\n   134→    (l) => looksLikeIngredient(l.trim()) || /^\\s*\\d/.test(l.trim())\n   135→  );\n   136→\n   137→  if (hasIngredientsBetween) {\n   138→    // Same recipe — keep only the first (earliest position) ALL_CAPS heading\n   139→    selected = [sortedCaps[0]];\n   140→  } else {\n   141→    // Likely multi-recipe page — keep all\n   142→    selected = allCapsSelected;\n   143→  }\n   144→}\n   145→```\n   146→\n   147→### Before / After\n   148→\n   149→**Before (CHLEBEK):**\n   150→- `allCapsSelected` = [`\"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\"` (pos 1), `\"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\"` (pos 2)]\n   151→- Guard sees 2 ALL_CAPS → returns both joined: `\"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM + WARZYWA I BOCZEK\"`\n   152→\n   153→**After (CHLEBEK):**\n   154→- Same `allCapsSelected`, but now checks lines between positions 1 and 2\n   155→- Line 3 (`\"500 g strączków...\"`) contains measurement \"g\" → `hasIngredientsBetween = true`\n   156→- Guard keeps only first: `\"CHLEBEK Z WARZYWAMI I BOCZKIEM\"` ✓\n   157→\n   158→**Safety for FINNISH FLATBREADS:**\n   159→- Two ALL_CAPS headings: `\"FINNISH MILK FLATBREADS\"` and `\"FINNISH POTATO FLATBREADS\"`\n   160→- Lines between them are recipe body text (instructions), NOT ingredients with measurements\n   161→- Actually — need to verify this. The FINNISH FLATBREADS test case has recipe text between the two titles which likely includes ingredients.\n   162→\n   163→### Risk Mitigation\n   164→\n   165→The ingredient-gap heuristic could be too aggressive if the FINNISH FLATBREADS page has ingredient lines between the two titles. To handle this, refine the check: require that **most** lines between headings (>50%) are ingredient-like, not just one. A multi-recipe page may have a few ingredient lines at the end of recipe 1, but the majority of lines between two recipe titles will be body text/instructions.\n   166→\n   167→Alternative refinement: check if ingredient lines appear **immediately after** the first heading (within the next 3 lines). Section headers in single-recipe layouts are typically followed directly by ingredients. Multi-recipe titles are followed by body text or instructions first.\n   168→\n   169→```typescript\n   170→// Refined: check if ingredients appear in the first 3 lines after the first heading\n   171→const immediateLines = lines.slice(firstPos + 1, Math.min(firstPos + 4, lastPos));\n   172→const hasImmediateIngredients = immediateLines.some(\n   173→  (l) => looksLikeIngredient(l.trim()) || /^\\s*\\d/.test(l.trim())\n   174→);\n   175→```\n   176→\n   177→For CHLEBEK: line immediately after the first heading is \"WARZYWA I BOCZEK\" (another heading), and the line after THAT is `\"500 g strączków...\"` (ingredient). So we need to look past intermediate headings. Better approach: check if ANY heading other than the first is immediately followed by ingredient lines.\n   178→\n   179→```typescript\n   180→// Check if any non-first ALL_CAPS heading is followed by ingredient content\n   181→// within 2 lines — this marks it as a section header, not a recipe title\n   182→const isSubHeader = sortedCaps.slice(1).every((cap) => {\n   183→  const nextLines = lines.slice(cap.position + 1, cap.position + 3);\n   184→  return nextLines.some(\n   185→    (l) => looksLikeIngredient(l.trim()) || /^\\s*\\d/.test(l.trim())\n   186→  );\n   187→});\n   188→\n   189→if (isSubHeader) {\n   190→  selected = [sortedCaps[0]];\n   191→} else {\n   192→  selected = allCapsSelected;\n   193→}\n   194→```\n   195→\n   196→This is more precise: it checks whether the **later** ALL_CAPS headings act like section headers (followed by ingredients) rather than recipe titles (followed by body text).\n   197→\n   198→### Expected Impact\n   199→\n   200→Fixes CHLEBEK without regressing FINNISH FLATBREADS, because the second FINNISH title is followed by its own recipe body text (instructions), not directly by ingredient lines.\n   201→\n   202→---\n   203→\n   204→## Change 3: First-line mixed-case title protection\n   205→\n   206→**Fixes:** Failure 3 (Faszerowana papryka)\n   207→\n   208→### Root Cause\n   209→\n   210→The scoring arithmetic makes it nearly impossible for a mixed-case line at position 0 to beat an ALL_CAPS line at position 1:\n   211→\n   212→| Candidate | rawScore (est.) | Position factor | ALL_CAPS bonus | Structural bonus | Final score |\n   213→|-----------|----------------|-----------------|----------------|-----------------|-------------|\n   214→| \"Faszerowana papryka\" (pos 0) | ~0.15 | ×1.12 | 0 | 0 | ~0.168 |\n   215→| \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" (pos 1) | ~0.12 | ×1.11 | +0.08 | +0.10 | ~0.313 |\n   216→\n   217→The ALL_CAPS bonuses (+0.18 combined) are designed for recipe books that use ALL_CAPS exclusively for titles. But bilingual cookbooks use mixed case for the primary language title and ALL_CAPS for the romanization/transliteration.\n   218→\n   219→The position-0 candidate is almost always the recipe title in every cookbook format observed. When a mixed-case candidate at position 0 has a reasonable embedding score, it should not lose to a position-1 ALL_CAPS candidate purely due to formatting bonuses.\n   220→\n   221→### Proposed Fix\n   222→\n   223→Add a **first-line title protection** rule after scoring, before the multi-title guard. When:\n   224→1. There is a mixed-case candidate at position 0 (or within the first 2 non-empty lines)\n   225→2. It passes the embedding threshold\n   226→3. The highest-scoring candidate is an ALL_CAPS line at position 1 (immediately following)\n   227→4. No other ALL_CAPS candidates exist further down\n   228→\n   229→Then: prefer the position-0 candidate, treating the ALL_CAPS line as a subtitle.\n   230→\n   231→```typescript\n   232→// First-line mixed-case title protection:\n   233→// If a mixed-case line at position 0 passes threshold and the only ALL_CAPS\n   234→// candidate is at position 1 (immediately following), the ALL_CAPS line is\n   235→// likely a subtitle/transliteration — prefer the first-line title.\n   236→if (selected.length >= 1) {\n   237→  const pos0 = selected.find(\n   238→    (s) => s.position === 0 && !isAllCaps(s.text)\n   239→  );\n   240→  const allCapsCandidates = selected.filter((s) => isAllCaps(s.text));\n   241→\n   242→  if (\n   243→    pos0 &&\n   244→    allCapsCandidates.length === 1 &&\n   245→    allCapsCandidates[0].position <= 2 && // immediately after title\n   246→    pos0.score >= threshold // has reasonable embedding score\n   247→  ) {\n   248→    // The ALL_CAPS line is a subtitle — remove it, keep position-0 title\n   249→    selected = selected.filter((s) => s !== allCapsCandidates[0]);\n   250→  }\n   251→}\n   252→```\n   253→\n   254→### Before / After\n   255→\n   256→**Before (Faszerowana papryka):**\n   257→- `selected` after threshold: both candidates survive\n   258→- Multi-title guard: 1 ALL_CAPS → collapse to highest score → `\"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\"` wins\n   259→- Result: `\"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\"` ✗\n   260→\n   261→**After (Faszerowana papryka):**\n   262→- First-line protection fires: pos0 = `\"Faszerowana papryka\"`, single ALL_CAPS at pos 1\n   263→- ALL_CAPS candidate removed as subtitle\n   264→- Result: `\"Faszerowana papryka\"` ✓\n   265→\n   266→### Safety for Other Tests\n   267→\n   268→- **MIXED SEED CRISPBREAD** (ALL_CAPS, single title, pos 0): pos0 IS all-caps → protection doesn't fire ✓\n   269→- **OVERNIGHT STRAIGHT PIZZA DOUGH** (ALL_CAPS, single title): same as above ✓\n   270→- **ARAYES SHRAK** (ALL_CAPS multi-word join): no mixed-case at pos 0 → doesn't fire ✓\n   271→- **FINNISH FLATBREADS** (two ALL_CAPS titles): `allCapsCandidates.length >= 2` → doesn't fire ✓\n   272→- **CHLEBEK** (ALL_CAPS title at pos 1, mixed-case category at pos 0): the category line `\"Lato | Dania główne\"` — need to check if this passes hard filters. It contains `\"|\"` and is a category header. `isLikelyGarbled` should catch this... let me check: it doesn't start lowercase, has valid vowel ratio, no garbled words. It would pass `passesHardFilters`. BUT: its embedding score as a recipe title should be very low (it's a category, not a dish name), so it likely won't pass the embedding threshold. If it does somehow pass: the protection would fire (mixed-case at pos 0, one ALL_CAPS at pos 1), incorrectly removing the real title.\n   273→\n   274→### Risk Mitigation for CHLEBEK Edge Case\n   275→\n   276→Add a guard: the position-0 mixed-case candidate must have a **minimum embedding rawScore** to qualify for protection. A category header like \"Lato | Dania główne\" will have a very low `rawScore` because it's not semantically similar to \"recipe name, dish title\". Set the minimum at the threshold value or at a fixed floor (e.g., rawScore ≥ 0.05).\n   277→\n   278→```typescript\n   279→// Additional guard: pos0 must have meaningful title similarity\n   280→const pos0Scored = scored.find(\n   281→  (s) => s.position === pos0.position && s.text === pos0.text\n   282→);\n   283→if (pos0Scored && pos0Scored.rawScore >= 0.05) {\n   284→  // ... fire protection\n   285→}\n   286→```\n   287→\n   288→Actually, checking: `pos0` is already in `selected`, meaning it already passed the threshold. The threshold is `max(0.08, bestThresholdScore * 0.7)`. So any candidate in `selected` has a meaningful score. The real question is whether \"Lato | Dania główne\" would be in `selected` at all.\n   289→\n   290→More robust guard: check if the position-0 candidate's **rawScore** is within a reasonable range of the ALL_CAPS candidate's rawScore (e.g., pos0.rawScore >= allCaps.rawScore * 0.5). A real title will have a comparable rawScore; a category header will have a much lower one.\n   291→\n   292→---\n   293→\n   294→## Change 4: Evaluation harness fix (out of scope for lib/text-classifier/)\n   295→\n   296→**Context:** Failure 4A (SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS — OCR reads \"/\" but expected title has \":\")\n   297→\n   298→The OCR text contains `\"/ COTTAGE CHEESE\"` where the printed book has `\": COTTAGE CHEESE\"`. The evaluation harness compares the extracted title against the filename-derived expected title. The filesystem may substitute `:` with `/` or vice versa, creating an impossible-to-match expected value.\n   299→\n   300→**Recommendation:** Normalize `/:` in the evaluation harness `titles_match` function. This is a change to `tools/title-loop/title-loop.py`, not to `lib/text-classifier/`. The algorithm is producing the correct output — it's the comparison that fails.\n   301→\n   302→---\n   303→\n   304→## Summary of Changes\n   305→\n   306→| Change | Target Failure | Files Modified | Risk | Complexity |\n   307→|--------|---------------|----------------|------|------------|\n   308→| Pre-merge continuation lines | F1 (Baked Eggs), F4B (SAFFRON join) | `title-extractor.ts` (`buildCandidates`) | Low — only affects lines starting with `/&+:(` | Low |\n   309→| Ingredient-gap in multi-title guard | F2 (CHLEBEK) | `title-extractor.ts` (multi-title guard block) | Medium — must not regress FINNISH | Medium |\n   310→| First-line mixed-case protection | F3 (Faszerowana papryka) | `title-extractor.ts` (after scoring, before multi-title guard) | Medium — needs rawScore guard for category headers | Medium |\n   311→| Eval harness separator normalization | F4A (SAFFRON OCR mismatch) | `title-loop.py` | None — eval-only change | Low |\n   312→\n   313→### Expected Accuracy After Changes\n   314→\n   315→- **Currently passing (4/8):** ARAYES SHRAK, FINNISH FLATBREADS, MIXED SEED CRISPBREAD, OVERNIGHT PIZZA DOUGH\n   316→- **Fixed by Change 1:** Baked Eggs ✓, SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS (partial — algorithm correct, eval still needs Change 4) ✓\n   317→- **Fixed by Change 2:** CHLEBEK ✓\n   318→- **Fixed by Change 3:** Faszerowana papryka ✓\n   319→- **Projected: 8/8 (100%)** with all changes including eval harness fix\n   320→\n   321→### Implementation Order\n   322→\n   323→1. **Change 1 (pre-merge)** — highest impact, lowest risk, fixes 2 failures\n   324→2. **Change 3 (first-line protection)** — independent of other changes, clear logic\n   325→3. **Change 2 (ingredient-gap)** — requires most careful testing against FINNISH FLATBREADS\n   326→4. **Change 4 (eval harness)** — trivial, independent\n   327→\n   328→### Tests to Add/Modify\n   329→\n   330→1. **New unit test:** \"merges continuation line starting with & into preceding line\" — verify `buildCandidates` produces merged candidate\n   331→2. **New unit test:** \"does not merge non-continuation second line\" — verify \"SHRAK\" (no leading symbol) is NOT pre-merged\n   332→3. **New unit test:** \"single recipe with ALL_CAPS section headers returns only title\" — CHLEBEK-style input\n   333→4. **New unit test:** \"bilingual page with mixed-case title at position 0 prefers it over ALL_CAPS subtitle\" — Faszerowana-style input\n   334→5. **Modify existing SAFFRON test** if the expected value needs updating for `/` vs `:`\n   335→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_017VcW5mg8g8GLn5Xde6iMaH","session_id":"688165a7-dc9e-4c33-9dca-71554537d527","uuid":"8ec5223b-9370-4fcd-9c0f-1fe4d4d1f53c"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_016e1dsXJkP1MZe8BwteX5df","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Iteration 9 Improvement Plan\n     2→\n     3→## Summary\n     4→\n     5→Two failures, two distinct root causes that share a common theme: the threshold gate has absolute veto power over candidates that pass all structural/hard filters, with no fallback when the candidate pool is small or the positional signal is unambiguous.\n     6→\n     7→The fixes are:\n     8→\n     9→1. **Pre-threshold bilingual protection** — move first-line detection before threshold filtering so ALL_CAPS bonuses can't inflate the threshold beyond the mixed-case title's reach.\n    10→2. **Empty-pool fallback** — when threshold filtering discards every candidate, fall back to the best positional candidate from the hard-filter-passing pool.\n    11→\n    12→These are complementary: fix 1 prevents failure 2 (Faszerowana papryka) by keeping the correct candidate in `selected`; fix 2 prevents failure 1 (Baked Eggs) by ensuring a sole survivor is never silently discarded.\n    13→\n    14→---\n    15→\n    16→## Failure 1: \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" → `''`\n    17→\n    18→### Root Cause\n    19→\n    20→The pre-merge step correctly produces the full candidate. It passes all hard filters (54 chars, no measurements, no metadata, not garbled). But the embedding scorer computes `rawScore = titleSim - max(headerSim, noiseSim)` and because ingredient words (Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce, Coriander) are semantically close to `HEADER_REFERENCE` (\"ingredients list, cooking directions\"), `headerSim ≈ titleSim` or `headerSim > titleSim`. The rawScore is near zero or negative. No bonus applies (mixed-case, not structural heading). The final score falls below `threshold = max(0.08, ...)` and the candidate is filtered out, returning `undefined`.\n    21→\n    22→The fundamental issue: **embeddings cannot distinguish \"dish named after its ingredients\" from \"fragment of an ingredient list\"**. The hard filters already make that distinction (ingredient lists have measurements, start with numbers, etc.), but their verdict is overruled by the embedding threshold.\n    23→\n    24→### Fix: Empty-pool fallback\n    25→\n    26→After the existing threshold filter (`let selected = scored.filter(s => s.score >= threshold)`), add a fallback:\n    27→\n    28→```typescript\n    29→// BEFORE (line ~389):\n    30→let selected = scored.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n    31→\n    32→// AFTER:\n    33→let selected = scored.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n    34→\n    35→// Empty-pool fallback: when threshold filtering discards every candidate,\n    36→// the hard filters' structural verdict should not be overruled by weak\n    37→// embedding differentiation. Return the best positional candidate.\n    38→if (selected.length === 0 && scored.length > 0) {\n    39→  // Prefer candidates near the top of the document (position 0 = most likely title).\n    40→  // Among ties, prefer higher score.\n    41→  const fallback = scored\n    42→    .slice()\n    43→    .sort((a, b) => a.position - b.position || b.score - a.score);\n    44→  selected = [fallback[0]];\n    45→}\n    46→```\n    47→\n    48→**Why this is safe:** Every candidate in `scored` already passed `passesHardFilters()` — no measurements, no metadata, no garbled text, not starting with a number, not lowercase-initial. If the entire pool of structurally-valid candidates has weak embedding differentiation, position is the strongest remaining signal (recipe titles appear at the top of the page). This fallback only fires when `selected` would otherwise be empty, so it cannot degrade any currently-passing test.\n    49→\n    50→### Expected behavior after fix\n    51→\n    52→- \"Baked Eggs with Feta, Harissa Tomato Sauce & Coriander\" is the only candidate in `scored` (the body text, ingredients, and metadata all fail hard filters).\n    53→- Threshold filter discards it (score < 0.08).\n    54→- Fallback selects it as the sole candidate → returns the correct title.\n    55→\n    56→---\n    57→\n    58→## Failure 2: \"Faszerowana papryka\" → `'PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM'`\n    59→\n    60→### Root Cause\n    61→\n    62→The first-line protection (lines 468–479) was designed for exactly this case: mixed-case title at position 0 followed by ALL_CAPS subtitle. But the protection runs **after** threshold filtering. The ALL_CAPS candidate \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" receives `+0.08` allCapsBonus + `+0.10` structuralBonus = `+0.18` on top of its rawScore. This inflates the threshold via `bestThresholdScore * 0.7`. The Polish mixed-case title \"Faszerowana papryka\" has a low rawScore (MiniLM is English-centric; short Polish text has low cosine similarity to the English TITLE_REFERENCE) and no bonuses. It falls below the inflated threshold, never enters `selected`, and the protection — which checks `selected.find(s => s.position === 0)` — silently becomes a no-op.\n    63→\n    64→The design is self-defeating: the protection requires the correct title to have already survived the threshold independently, but it's needed precisely when the title **cannot** survive the threshold.\n    65→\n    66→### Fix: Pre-threshold bilingual detection\n    67→\n    68→Move the bilingual detection to operate on the full `scored` array (before threshold filtering). When the pattern is detected, force-include the position-0 candidate and suppress the ALL_CAPS subtitle.\n    69→\n    70→```typescript\n    71→// BEFORE (lines 385-389):\n    72→const bestThresholdScore = Math.max(...scored.map((s) => s.thresholdScore));\n    73→const threshold = Math.max(0.08, bestThresholdScore * 0.7);\n    74→let selected = scored.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n    75→\n    76→// AFTER:\n    77→// --- Pre-threshold bilingual title detection ---\n    78→// When a mixed-case candidate at position 0 is followed by a single ALL_CAPS\n    79→// candidate at position ≤ 2 in the FULL scored pool, this is a bilingual recipe\n    80→// page (e.g., Polish title + ALL_CAPS Korean romanization). Suppress the ALL_CAPS\n    81→// candidate before computing threshold so its bonuses don't inflate the threshold\n    82→// beyond the mixed-case title's reach.\n    83→//\n    84→// This replaces the post-threshold guard at lines 468-479 which was ineffective\n    85→// because it required both candidates to survive threshold independently.\n    86→let scoredForThreshold = scored;\n    87→const prePos0 = scored.find((s) => s.position === 0 && !isAllCaps(s.text));\n    88→const preAllCaps = scored.filter((s) => isAllCaps(s.text));\n    89→if (\n    90→  prePos0 &&\n    91→  preAllCaps.length === 1 &&\n    92→  preAllCaps[0].position <= 2\n    93→) {\n    94→  // Remove the ALL_CAPS subtitle from threshold computation AND from selection.\n    95→  scoredForThreshold = scored.filter((s) => s !== preAllCaps[0]);\n    96→}\n    97→\n    98→const bestThresholdScore = Math.max(...scoredForThreshold.map((s) => s.thresholdScore));\n    99→const threshold = Math.max(0.08, bestThresholdScore * 0.7);\n   100→let selected = scoredForThreshold.filter((s) => s.score >= threshold);\n   101→```\n   102→\n   103→Then **remove or disable** the old post-threshold first-line protection (lines 468–479) since it's now redundant.\n   104→\n   105→**Why this is safe:**\n   106→- The guard condition is identical to the old one: mixed-case at position 0, exactly 1 ALL_CAPS candidate at position ≤ 2.\n   107→- `preAllCaps.length === 1` ensures it never fires on genuine multi-recipe pages (which have ≥ 2 ALL_CAPS headings).\n   108→- Moving it pre-threshold only changes behavior when the mixed-case title would otherwise be below threshold — which is precisely the failure case.\n   109→\n   110→### Expected behavior after fix\n   111→\n   112→- `scored` contains \"Faszerowana papryka\" (pos 0, mixed-case) and \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" (pos 1, ALL_CAPS).\n   113→- Pre-threshold detection identifies the bilingual pattern: pos0 is mixed-case, exactly 1 ALL_CAPS at pos ≤ 2.\n   114→- \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" is removed from `scoredForThreshold`.\n   115→- Threshold is now computed from \"Faszerowana papryka\" alone — much lower, achievable.\n   116→- \"Faszerowana papryka\" enters `selected` → returned as the title.\n   117→\n   118→---\n   119→\n   120→## Interaction between the two fixes\n   121→\n   122→The fixes are independent and non-conflicting:\n   123→\n   124→| Scenario | Fix 1 (fallback) | Fix 2 (bilingual) | Which fires? |\n   125→|---|---|---|---|\n   126→| Baked Eggs (sole candidate, below threshold) | Catches it | N/A (no ALL_CAPS) | Fix 1 |\n   127→| Faszerowana papryka (bilingual, threshold inflated) | Would also catch it as fallback | Prevents the problem entirely | Fix 2 (fix 1 is not needed) |\n   128→| Normal recipes (candidates above threshold) | Never fires | Never fires (no pattern match or >1 ALL_CAPS) | Neither |\n   129→| Multi-recipe ALL_CAPS pages | Never fires (candidates pass threshold) | Never fires (≥2 ALL_CAPS) | Neither |\n   130→\n   131→Fix 2 is the primary fix for failure 2. Fix 1 is the primary fix for failure 1. But fix 1 would also serve as a secondary safety net for failure 2 if fix 2 somehow didn't fire — defense in depth.\n   132→\n   133→---\n   134→\n   135→## Changes to make (ordered)\n   136→\n   137→### Change 1: Pre-threshold bilingual detection\n   138→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n   139→**Location:** Before line 385 (threshold computation)\n   140→**Action:** Add bilingual detection on full `scored` array. Suppress the sole ALL_CAPS subtitle from threshold computation and selection when the pattern matches.\n   141→\n   142→### Change 2: Empty-pool fallback\n   143→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n   144→**Location:** After line 389 (`let selected = scored.filter(...)`)\n   145→**Action:** Add fallback that selects the best positional candidate when `selected` is empty.\n   146→\n   147→### Change 3: Remove old post-threshold first-line protection\n   148→**File:** `lib/text-classifier/title-extractor.ts`\n   149→**Location:** Lines 468–479\n   150→**Action:** Remove the entire block. It's replaced by the pre-threshold version (change 1) and was ineffective in the failure case anyway.\n   151→\n   152→### No other changes needed\n   153→\n   154→- Hard filters: working correctly for both cases.\n   155→- Pre-merge continuation logic: working correctly (Baked Eggs candidate is correctly merged).\n   156→- Multi-title guard: not involved in either failure.\n   157→- Dedup logic: not involved in either failure.\n   158→- Structural heading detection: not involved in failure 1; correctly identifies PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM in failure 2 but this is handled by the bilingual guard.\n   159→\n   160→---\n   161→\n   162→## Risk Assessment\n   163→\n   164→**Risk of regression on passing tests:**\n   165→- **Low.** Fix 1 (fallback) only fires when `selected` is empty — this never happens for currently-passing tests. Fix 2 (bilingual) only fires when there's a mixed-case pos-0 with exactly 1 ALL_CAPS at pos ≤ 2 — this pattern doesn't appear in currently-passing tests (they have either 0 or ≥2 ALL_CAPS headings, or no mixed-case at pos 0).\n   166→\n   167→**Risk of over-fitting:**\n   168→- **Moderate but acceptable.** The bilingual guard is specific to a real pattern (bilingual cookbooks) rather than a one-off hack. The empty-pool fallback is a general safety net that addresses a genuine design gap (hard filters should not be overruled by weak embedding signals).\n   169→\n   170→**What could still go wrong:**\n   171→- A recipe where position 0 is genuinely not the title (e.g., book name on first line, recipe title on line 3). The fallback would return the wrong line. Mitigation: this is rare in the test corpus and the hard filters would likely catch book names (too long, or garbled).\n   172→- A recipe where position 0 is mixed-case and position 1 is ALL_CAPS but the ALL_CAPS line is the real title (not a subtitle). The bilingual guard would suppress it. Mitigation: the `position ≤ 2` and `length === 1` constraints are very specific.\n   173→\n   174→## Expected accuracy after changes\n   175→\n   176→- Iteration 8: 75% (6/8 passing, 2 failing)\n   177→- Projected: **100% (8/8 passing)** — both failures addressed with targeted, non-overlapping fixes.\n   178→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_017VcW5mg8g8GLn5Xde6iMaH","session_id":"688165a7-dc9e-4c33-9dca-71554537d527","uuid":"9122c038-b7ec-485f-b848-f34ea3b9c5d0"}
