{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_018yEQKVxPZxMD3Y38Rxj9Aw","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a thorough understanding of the problem. Let me analyze the current failure and think about the right fix.\n\nThe single failing case in iteration 9:\n- **File**: `Faszerowana papryka.real.txt`\n- **Expected**: `Faszerowana papryka`\n- **Got**: `PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM`\n\nThe root cause is clear from the feedback: the bilingual detection guard at line 392 requires `preAllCaps.length === 1`, but this document has 4 ALL_CAPS candidates (PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM, NA 3 PAPRYKI, SKŁADNIKI, WARZYWA). \n\nSo the suppression doesn't fire. The feedback suggests I should shift from a global count to a positional check—specifically, whether the ALL_CAPS candidate immediately following the title appears to be a romanization or translation, independent of how many other ALL_CAPS lines exist elsewhere in the document.\n\nThe approach is to combine a positional check (is the ALL_CAPS candidate at position ≤ 2?) with a semantic proximity check (does it embed close to the mixed-case candidate?) rather than relying on counts. So when there's a mixed-case candidate at position 0 and an ALL_CAPS candidate nearby, I'd check if they're semantically similar translations of each other, and suppress the ALL_CAPS one if they are.\n\nLooking at the other ALL_CAPS candidates that might still win after suppressing PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM, there's NA 3 PAPRYKI at position 5, which appears to be a serving size rather than a structural heading. I need to pick between suppressing the bilingual candidate entirely or boosting the position-0 option. The cleaner approach is bilingual detection — relaxing it to catch cases where an ALL_CAPS candidate near the top looks like a translation of the mixed-case heading. I could detect this through semantic similarity in embeddings, lexical overlap like \"papryka\" matching \"PAPRIKA\", or simpler heuristics.\n\nThe simplest rule: if position 0 is mixed-case and there's an ALL_CAPS candidate at position ≤ 2, suppress the ALL_CAPS one. This avoids needing semantic checks, but I need to make sure position 0 isn't just garbage that would accidentally suppress a legitimate title. Since position-0 candidates already pass hard filters, this should be safe. Let me verify this doesn't break other test cases — we're at 87.5% and need to fix just this one without regressing.\n\nActually, I could use embedding similarity as a safety check: compare the position-0 mixed-case candidate with the ALL_CAPS candidate at position ≤ 2, and only suppress if their cosine similarity is high enough, confirming they're both referring to the same dish name or translation. 0.5), they're likely translations and we suppress the ALL_CAPS one.\n\nBut wait — we already have embeddings for all candidates in the rawScored array. We can compute similarity between the position-0 candidate and the early ALL_CAPS candidate.\n\nLet me draft the improvement plan now.\n\nKey changes:\n1. **Relax bilingual detection**: Remove `preAllCaps.length === 1` guard. Instead, when position 0 has a mixed-case candidate, find ALL_CAPS candidates at position ≤ 2. For each, compute embedding similarity with the position-0 candidate. If similarity is above a threshold (e.g., 0.4), suppress the ALL_CAPS candidate from scoring/threshold computation.\n\n2. **Why embedding similarity works here**: Both \"Faszerowana papryka\" and \"PAPRIKA GYERAN-JJIM\" are dish names and will embed close to each other. Section headers like \"SKŁADNIKI\" won't embed close to \"Faszerowana papryka\" — they embed close to HEADER_REFERENCE instead.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3352,"cache_read_input_tokens":31930,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3352},"output_tokens":9,"service_tier":"standard","inference_g